{"id":"quant-ph/0205179","submitter":"Robert M. Gingrich","authors":"Robert M. Gingrich and Christoph Adami","title":"Quantum Entanglement of Moving Bodies","comments":"4 pages, 2 figures. An error was corrected in the numerical data and\n  hence the discussion of the data was changed. Also, references were added.\n  Another example was added to the paper","journal-ref":"Phys.Rev. Lett. 89 (2002) 270402","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.89.270402","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We study the properties of quantum information and quantum entanglement in\nmoving frames. We show that the entanglement between the spins and the momenta\nof two particles can be interchanged under a Lorentz transformation, so that a\npair of particles that is entangled in spin but not momentum in one reference\nframe, may, in another frame, be entangled in momentum at the expense of\nspin-entanglement. Similarly, entanglement between momenta may be transferred\nto spin under a Lorentz transformation. While spin and momentum entanglement\neach is not Lorentz invariant, the joint entanglement of the wave function is.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 29 May 2002 18:56:11 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 20 Jun 2002 02:51:43 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 12 Jul 2002 23:45:50 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Sat, 7 Dec 2002 01:58:52 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
{"id":"quant-ph/0205186","submitter":"Dr. Anjana Sinha","authors":"Anjana Sinha and Y.P. Varshni","title":"Energy spectra of two electrons in a circular quantum dot","comments":"10 pages, revised version","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  The electron interaction energy of two interacting electrons in a circular\nquantum dot (with hard wall confinement) is investigated in the framework of\nthe semi-classical Wentzel-Kramers-Brillouin (WKB) approximation. The two\nelectrons are assumed to be in an infinitely deep well of radius $r_0$, in a\nsimple configuration with one electron fixed at the origin. The corresponding\nSchrodinger equation, with hard wall boundary conditions, is also solved\nexactly by numerical integration. It is observed that the agreement between the\ntwo energy values is quite good, suggesting that the WKB approximation works\nwell for such a confined quantum system as well. This may provide motivation to\nextend this to more realistic confined potentials.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 30 May 2002 08:05:02 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 27 Aug 2002 11:05:27 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
